    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:bd957676-c1f1-4b31-a1ea-a9d9eb32c6d8",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 71-year-old man who appears older than his stated age, with a lean frame and a slightly stooped posture. Over the past several months he has become noticeably more fatigued and pale, often needing to sit and rest after routine activities. He describes intermittent crampy lower abdominal discomfort, reduced stamina, and a change in his bowel habits, alternating between constipation and looser stools. He has also noticed his clothes fitting more loosely after an unintentional weight loss of about 7 kg over the last 5 months. On some days he reports a sensation of incomplete evacuation and occasional dark or maroon-tinged stool, though he initially attributed this to hemorrhoids.\n\nHe is a retired high school history teacher who now works part-time at a local museum two days a week. His lifestyle is generally quiet and structured; he lives with his wife, enjoys woodworking in his garage, gardening, and meeting a small group of friends for coffee on weekend mornings. He used to be more physically active but has cut back on long walks because of fatigue and lightheadedness. His diet is mixed, with relatively low fiber intake and frequent consumption of processed meats and convenience foods, especially since retirement.\n\nSocially, {patientName} is close to his wife and adult daughter, both of whom have become concerned by his declining energy and appetite. He is a former smoker with a 25-pack-year history, having quit about 15 years ago, and drinks 1-2 beers on several evenings each week. He is generally independent in activities of daily living, but lately his wife has taken over more household errands because he tires easily. He presents as thoughtful and mildly anxious, particularly about the possibility that his recent symptoms may represent something serious.\n\nOn examination, he would likely appear pale with mild conjunctival pallor and evidence of weight loss, but without acute distress. His abdomen is soft with mild diffuse lower abdominal tenderness and no overt peritoneal signs. The overall picture is of an older adult with insidious gastrointestinal symptoms, anemia-related fatigue, and constitutional changes consistent with an undiagnosed colonic malignancy."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:3cf17634-f1f2-4c7a-a2ad-4fc7b89df1e8",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of essential hypertension and hyperlipidemia, both reasonably controlled in primary care. He also has benign prostatic hyperplasia with mild nocturia and gastroesophageal reflux disease that is intermittent and diet-related. There is no known prior history of inflammatory bowel disease or previously diagnosed colorectal cancer. He recalls a screening colonoscopy more than 12 years ago in which a small polyp was reportedly removed, but he did not maintain recommended surveillance follow-up.\n\nOver the last 6 months, {patientName} has experienced progressive fatigue, reduced exercise tolerance, decreased appetite, intermittent bloating, and altered bowel movements. He delayed seeking evaluation because the symptoms were gradual and he assumed they were related to aging, stress, and hemorrhoids. He denies frank vomiting but has had occasional nausea and a sense of abdominal fullness after meals. There has been no prior hospitalization for bowel obstruction, though he has visited urgent care once in the past year for dizziness, where mild anemia was noted and outpatient follow-up was advised.\n\nHis past medical history is otherwise notable for osteoarthritis of the knees and a remote appendectomy in young adulthood. He is a former smoker and drinks alcohol socially in modest amounts. He lives at home, manages his own medications, and has no cognitive impairment. Functional status has recently declined from fully active to limited in prolonged walking and heavier physical tasks because of fatigue and weakness."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}